<p><strong>Product</strong>: <a href="https://www.filefillet.com/?ref=about" target="_blank">FileFillet - Efficiently manage files on MacOS</a><br>
<strong>Price</strong>: $7.99</p>
<p>There are a ton of solutions available to make it easier for you to copy/move your files in macOS. In essence, they give you a shelf. You drag files on to it from the Finder, and then drag them to a folder of your choice.</p>
<p>Incomplete list of competitors of FileFillet.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.eternalstorms.at/yoink/mac/" target="_blank">Yoink for Mac - Simplify and Improve Drag and Drop</a> ($8.99)</li>
<li><a href="https://dropoverapp.com/" target="_blank">Dropover - Easier Drag and Drop on your Mac.</a>(Free)</li>
<li><a href="https://pilotmoon.com/dropshelf/" target="_blank">Dropshelf</a> (Free for the time being)</li>
<li><a href="https://fiplab.com/apps/space-drop-for-mac" target="_blank">Space Drop for Mac - FIPLAB</a> ($7.99)</li>
<li><a href="https://www.bru.build/gladys-for-macos" target="_blank">Gladys for macOS — BRU.BUILD</a> (Free)</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="filefillet-shelves-different">FileFillet Shelves Different</h2>
<p>FileFillet does something different. It gives you a similar shelf.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_c4a729f3205a44e5a9669523ddfb8b2e/_image_cache/16a25796-86ea-428c-bafa-7782708e2fca.png" alt="Destination Shelf" width="592" height="876" data-action="zoom"><span class="caption">Destination Shelf</span></p>
<p>But it is significantly different. You designate your destination folders in advance, and drop your files straight into chosen folder. One less step. Some setup on the frontend.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_c4a729f3205a44e5a9669523ddfb8b2e/_image_cache/54ef0d7b-73b6-435d-be44-ef505ac5c87a.png" alt="Choices" width="682" height="1104" data-action="zoom"><span class="caption">Choices</span></p>
<p>You have some well designed choices in the setup. You can copy or move the files. You can have the grid setup the way you want.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_c4a729f3205a44e5a9669523ddfb8b2e/_image_cache/97962bc3-07a7-4c29-952e-c9305aa7a487.png" alt="Prerences" width="1504" height="1356" data-action="zoom"><span class="caption">Prerences</span></p>
<p>FileFillet lets you assign a keyboard shortcut to call its panel. Holding down the ⌃key puts the panel right next to the cursor.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_c4a729f3205a44e5a9669523ddfb8b2e/_image_cache/9b267ebf-e4cf-40fa-ace1-358b463327e0.png" alt="More Choices" width="1504" height="748" data-action="zoom"><span class="caption">More Choices</span></p>
<p>You have some control over how you want the panel to look.</p>
<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
<p>If you like to keep your files in the right place for you, and do a lot of moving your files around to achieve peak organizational zen, FileFillet is a good solution.</p>
<p>I recommend FileFillet to improve your file organizational skills. This is a good program for that task.</p>
<p>macosxguru at the gmail thingie.</p>
